#### Ch-3: Identifying and Caring for House Plants
*Strategy:* Diagnose + Research (Expert Role)
*See also:* Ho-7: Gardening & Landscaping (for outdoor plants), Ch-1: Shopping Your Values (before buying the next one)
*My Man Jeeves:* _It would appear that the houseplant industry sells one a living organism accompanied by a plastic tag reading "bright indirect light" and "water when dry" --- instructions of such imprecision that they might apply equally to a cactus or a fern, two species whose survival requirements are, if one may say so, diametrically opposed. The plant then expires, and the owner arrives at the conclusion that they lack a "green thumb," which is a character trait the horticultural trade appears to have invented to account for the fact that they sold one a tropical understory species and disclosed nothing material about it. An interior landscaper in a properly staffed household would know the species, the light requirements, the humidity range, and the watering schedule. One's Agent possesses the same knowledge and is, moreover, capable of identifying the plant from a photograph._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
Act as an experienced indoor plant specialist.
Here is my situation:
— The plant: [name if known, or describe it — leaf shape,
  size, any flowers, the tag if you still have it.
  Or: send a photo.]
— The problem: [yellowing leaves / brown tips / drooping /
  dropping leaves / white spots / bugs / not growing /
  just bought it and want to keep it alive]
— My conditions: [which direction do the windows face,
  how much light does the spot get, how often do I water,
  do I use tap water or filtered, is there a heating vent
  or AC draft nearby]
— My skill level: [I've killed every plant I've owned /
  I keep a few alive / I have a collection]
Please:
1. Identify the plant if I haven't, and tell me its actual
   care requirements — not the tag version
2. Diagnose what's likely wrong based on my description
3. Give me a specific care routine: how often to water,
   how to check if it needs water, light and humidity needs
4. Tell me the one thing most people get wrong with this
   species
:::
*What to do with the Output:* Change one variable at a time and wait two weeks before concluding it didn't work. Plants respond slowly. If the diagnosis is "too much water," your job is to resist watering for longer than feels comfortable. Most houseplants are killed by overwatering, not neglect.

::: tip
Send a photo. Your Agent can identify most common houseplants from a clear photo of the leaves and growth habit. Include a photo of the problem area --- the yellowing leaf, the brown tips, the white residue on the soil. Visual diagnosis is dramatically more accurate than text description for plants.
:::


::: science
The "green thumb" is not a personality trait. It is a knowledge gap. A 2015 study in _HortScience_ found that the primary barrier keeping consumers from buying --- and successfully keeping --- indoor plants was a deficit of practical knowledge about watering and light requirements, not inexperience or lack of botanical talent.[^ch3-1] University extension services consistently identify overwatering as the leading cause of houseplant death --- a problem that disappears once you know the species-specific requirements. Know the plant. Follow the requirements. That's the whole secret.
:::


::: also
To make this Expert Role persistent across sessions, save it as a *Project* (Claude), *Gem* (Gemini), or *Custom GPT* (ChatGPT). See [Appendix G](06-appendix-g-feature-table.xhtml).
:::


[^ch3-1]: Rihn, A.L., Khachatryan, H., Campbell, B., Hall, C. & Behe, B. (2015). "[Consumer response to novel indoor foliage plant attributes: Evidence from a conjoint experiment and gaze analysis](https://doi.org/10.21273/HORTSCI.50.10.1524)." _HortScience_, 50(10), 1524--1530. 42% of consumers identified maintenance requirements as their primary barrier to keeping indoor plants.

