#### Ch-7: Meal Planning and Grocery Shopping
*Strategy:* Research + Prepare
*See also:* Ch-5: Cooking and Culinary Skills (for what to do once you're in the kitchen), Ch-1: Shopping Your Values (for sourcing and certification), Li-9: Household Budget (for the financial side), H-8: Wellness and Nutrition Coach (for dietary needs)
*My Man Jeeves:* _One observes that the average household disposes of roughly 30% of the food it purchases --- a figure that would prompt an inquiry at any reasonably managed institution. The difficulty is not, in the main, one of appetite or intention. It is a planning problem conducted under conditions that would defeat most logistics professionals: variable schedules, unpredictable preferences, perishable inventory with no standardized shelf life, and a weekly budget that must account for nutrition, taste, household politics, and whatever happens to be on sale. The household that employs a cook also employs a person who plans meals before writing the shopping list, not after. This is the sequence that matters. One's Agent is capable of working backward from what one wishes to eat, through what one already has, to what one actually needs to buy --- a reversal that reliably reduces both the bill and the bin._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I need to plan meals for the week and build a grocery list.
My household: [number of people, ages, any dietary
restrictions or preferences]
My budget: [weekly grocery budget, or "as low as reasonable"]
What I already have: [check your fridge, freezer, and pantry
--- list anything that needs to be used soon]
My schedule this week: [which nights are busy, when do I
have time to cook, any nights eating out]
My cooking skill and effort level: [be honest --- 20 minutes
max on weeknights / I can do an hour on Sunday / I hate
cooking but I need to eat]
Please:
1. Suggest 5--7 dinners that share ingredients to minimize
   waste and cost --- show me the overlap
2. Build a grocery list organized by store section, with
   estimated prices for my area
3. Flag which items are worth buying in bulk or frozen vs. fresh
4. Identify what I should prep on Sunday to make weeknights
   faster
5. Estimate total grocery cost for the week
:::
*What to do with the Output:* The hardest part of feeding a household is not the cooking. It is the deciding --- what to make, what to buy, what everyone will eat. That daily cognitive load is what meal planning offloads to your Agent. Start with one week. Do not plan a month --- you will not follow it. Run the plan, note what you actually ate and what went to waste, and feed that back to your Agent the following week. The plan improves as the data improves. After three weeks, your Agent knows your household better than any meal kit service.

::: science
The USDA estimates that the average American household wastes 31.9% of its food, costing roughly $1,500 per year.[^ch7-1] The primary driver is not spoilage --- it is overbuying and poor planning. Research consistently identifies meal planning as one of the most effective household-level interventions, reducing food waste by roughly a quarter even without other changes.[^ch7-2] The math is straightforward: plan meals, buy what you need, use what you buy.
:::


::: tip
Take a photo of the inside of your fridge and pantry before you plan. Send the photos to your Agent with the spec. It can identify what you have, suggest meals that use up what's about to expire, and build the grocery list around what you're missing --- not what a recipe assumes you're starting from scratch with.
:::


::: fairness
Grocery budgets are not equal, and "healthy eating on a budget" advice that assumes access to a well-stocked grocery store is useless if you live in a food desert. Tell your Agent where you actually shop --- including dollar stores, ethnic markets, and discount grocers. It will plan around your real options, not the Whole Foods fantasy. If SNAP benefits are part of your budget, say so --- your Agent can optimize around benefit timing and eligible items without judgment.
:::


[^ch7-1]: U.S. Department of Agriculture, Economic Research Service. ["Food Loss and Waste."](https://www.ers.usda.gov/topics/food-markets-prices/food-service-industry/food-loss-and-waste/) ERS estimates that 30--40% of the US food supply is lost or wasted, costing the average household over $1,500 annually.
[^ch7-2]: NRDC (2017). ["Wasted: How America Is Losing Up to 40 Percent of Its Food."](https://www.nrdc.org/resources/wasted-how-america-losing-40-percent-its-food) Meal planning consistently appears in food waste reduction literature as among the most effective household-level strategies.

