#### Ch-8: Cleaning and Laundry
*Strategy:* Research + Navigate (Expert Role)
*See also:* Ch-6: Optimizing Manual Chores (for scheduling and systems), Ho-1: Maintaining Your Home (cleaning is maintenance)
*My Man Jeeves:* _It is perhaps worth observing that garment care labels employ a system of hieroglyphics that the International Organization for Standardization published in 1971 and has not, in any meaningful sense, explained to the public since. The triangle means bleach. The circle means dry clean. The number of dots inside the iron means something one has either memorized or has not --- and the consequence of guessing incorrectly is a $60 sweater reduced to a size suitable for a medium-sized cat. Similarly, the cleaning product aisle offers approximately 40 specialized solutions for surfaces that require, in practice, about four. The household that employs staff finds these matters handled by persons who know that wool felts in hot water, that bleach and ammonia must never meet, and that the "stainless" in stainless steel is aspirational. One's Agent possesses this same knowledge and is available at the moment the red wine hits the white shirt, which is to say, the moment it is actually needed._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
Act as a textile care and cleaning specialist.
My situation: [choose one or more]
— Stain emergency: [what stain, what fabric, how long ago,
  what I've already tried]
— Laundry question: [specific garment or fabric I don't know
  how to wash, what the care label says if I can read it]
— Cleaning question: [what surface or area, what the mess is,
  what products I have on hand]
— General: I want to understand what cleaning products I
  actually need and what's redundant
Please:
1. Give me the specific fix or method, step by step
2. Explain *why* it works (the chemistry, briefly) so I can
   generalize to similar problems
3. Tell me what will make it worse --- the thing most people
   try first that sets the stain or damages the surface
4. If I need a product I probably don't have, tell me what
   common household item substitutes
:::
*What to do with the Output:* For stain emergencies, act immediately --- stains set with time and heat. For laundry sorting and product questions, save your Agent's answers in a note on your phone. You will look this up again. Build a household cleaning reference over time: one conversation for stains, one for surfaces, one for laundry. After a few sessions, you will know 90% of what you need and only consult for the unusual cases.

::: science
The chemistry of stain removal follows consistent principles: protein stains (blood, egg, milk) require cold water and enzymatic cleaners because heat denatures the protein and bonds it to fabric. Tannin stains (wine, coffee, tea) respond to oxidizing agents. Grease responds to surfactants. Most commercial stain removers are combinations of these three mechanisms with marketing attached. Understanding which mechanism your stain requires eliminates the guesswork --- and the shelf of 12 products you bought for 12 different stains that all needed the same enzyme.[^ch8-1]
:::


::: tip
Take a photo of the care label and send it to your Agent. It will decode every symbol and tell you, in plain English, exactly how to wash the garment. This is faster than Googling "what does the square with a circle inside it mean" every laundry day.
:::


::: meme
Bleach and ammonia together produce chloramine gas. This is not a cleaning hack. This is a chemical weapon. Your Agent will flag dangerous combinations before you mix them. If nothing else in this entry sticks, this does: never mix bleach with ammonia, vinegar, or rubbing alcohol. Ask your Agent before combining any cleaning products you are unsure about.
:::


[^ch8-1]: University extension textile care guides consistently categorize stains by chemistry: protein (cold water + enzyme), tannin (oxidizer), and grease (surfactant). See e.g. Olson, K. (2003). "Stain Removal for Washable Fabrics." University of Minnesota Extension.

