#### Ch-9: Pet Care and Training
*Strategy:* Research + Navigate (Expert Role)
*See also:* H-8: Wellness and Nutrition Coach (same Expert Role pattern for a different species), Ch-1: Shopping Your Values (pet food and products), Li-1: Difficult Conversations (for end-of-life decisions with your vet)
*My Man Jeeves:* _The pet industry generates approximately $150 billion in annual revenue in the United States alone --- a figure that rather complicates the notion that one is simply caring for an animal. One is, in fact, navigating a market that sells grain-free dog food for $80 a bag on the basis of a theory whose scientific support remains contested --- the FDA's investigation found a correlation with dilated cardiomyopathy but not definitive causation, training services at $150 per session from practitioners who may hold no credential of any kind, and "wellness plans" at the veterinary office that bundle services one's pet may not require. Meanwhile, the questions that actually determine an animal's quality of life --- appropriate nutrition for the species and breed, exercise requirements, behavioral needs, when a symptom warrants a vet visit and when it does not --- are answerable from the veterinary literature, which the average pet owner has neither the time nor the training to consult. One's Agent has read the literature. It cannot examine your pet, but it can prepare you for every conversation with someone who can._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
Act as a veterinary-informed pet care advisor.
(You are not a veterinarian. You cannot diagnose or treat.
You can help me prepare for vet visits, understand my options,
and make informed decisions.)
My pet: [species, breed if known, age, weight, spayed/neutered,
any known health conditions]
My question: [choose one or more]
— Behavior: [describe the behavior, when it started, triggers,
  what I've tried]
— Nutrition: [what I'm currently feeding, any concerns, budget]
— Health: [symptom I'm seeing, how long, severity --- or:
  preparing for a vet visit and want to know what to ask]
— Training: [what I want to teach, what isn't working,
  my pet's history with training]
— Life stage: [new pet setup / senior care / end-of-life
  planning]
Please:
1. Give me the evidence-based answer, not the pet store answer
2. If this warrants a vet visit, say so clearly and tell me
   what to tell the vet
3. If this is a training or behavior issue, use positive
   reinforcement methods only
4. Tell me what the pet industry is likely to upsell me on
   and whether it's worth it
:::
*What to do with the Output:* For health concerns, your Agent is triage, not treatment. If it says "see your vet," see your vet --- and bring the Agent's summary with you. For training, consistency matters more than technique: get everyone in the household on the same protocol before you start. For nutrition, make one change at a time and observe for two weeks. For end-of-life decisions, your Agent can walk you through quality-of-life assessment scales and help you prepare for the conversation with your vet — but it cannot make the decision. See Li-1: Difficult Conversations.

*Common pet care Expert Role specs:*
::: prompt
Act as a veterinary-informed pet care advisor. I just adopted a
[species, age, breed]. What do I need for the first two weeks ---
supplies, vet visit checklist, household setup, and the most
common new-owner mistakes for this species?
:::
::: prompt
Act as a positive-reinforcement animal trainer. My [species]
[behavior: won't stop barking / scratches furniture / bites /
pulls on leash / won't use the litter box / is aggressive with
other animals]. What is this behavior communicating, and what's
the evidence-based approach?
:::
::: prompt
Act as a veterinary-informed pet care advisor. My [species] is
[age] and showing signs of [symptom]. I have a vet appointment
on [date]. Help me prepare: what should I observe and record
before the visit, what questions should I ask, and what tests
or treatments might the vet recommend?
:::

::: fairness
Veterinary costs have increased 60% over the past decade, and pet insurance --- unlike human health insurance --- is unregulated in most states. The reader who cannot afford a $3,000 emergency surgery is not a bad pet owner. They are a person living in a country that has no safety net for veterinary care. Your Agent can help you find low-cost clinics, veterinary schools that offer reduced-price services, breed-specific rescue organizations that sometimes fund medical care, and payment plans. It can also help you understand when a $200 vet visit is genuinely necessary and when the symptom is something you can monitor at home --- a distinction that saves money and reduces unnecessary stress for the animal.[^ch9-1]
:::


::: science
The American Veterinary Society of Animal Behavior published a position statement in 2021 confirming that positive reinforcement is the most effective and least harmful training method across species, and that dominance-based techniques (alpha rolls, leash corrections, shock collars) increase fear, anxiety, and aggression.[^ch9-2] If a trainer --- or a search result --- recommends "showing the dog who's boss," the science says they are wrong. Your Agent draws from the current evidence base, not the 1990s.
:::


::: also
To make this Expert Role persistent across sessions, save it as a *Project* (Claude), *Gem* (Gemini), or *Custom GPT* (ChatGPT). See [Appendix G](06-appendix-g-feature-table.xhtml).
:::


[^ch9-1]: Bureau of Labor Statistics, Consumer Price Index for Veterinary Services. Veterinary costs have risen significantly faster than general inflation over the past decade. See also AVMA data on cost as a barrier to veterinary care.
[^ch9-2]: American Veterinary Society of Animal Behavior. ["Position Statement on Humane Dog Training."](https://avsab.org/resources/position-statements/) AVSAB recommends reward-based training and advises against dominance-based methods.

---

#### Ch-10: Seasonal Maintenance
*Strategy:* Prepare + Navigate
*See also:* Ho-1: Maintaining Your Home (for ongoing maintenance), Ho-2: Home Repair and DIY (for when maintenance reveals a repair), Ch-6: Optimizing Manual Chores (for scheduling the recurring tasks)
*My Man Jeeves:* _A house, if one may observe, operates on a calendar that its occupants rarely consult. The gutters require attention in autumn. The HVAC filters require replacement quarterly. The water heater requires flushing annually --- a task that a vanishingly small fraction of homeowners perform, the remainder discovering the consequence when the unit fails, which it does, on average, at the ten-year mark, on a Saturday, when plumbers charge emergency rates. The difficulty is not that these tasks are complex. Most require thirty minutes and no specialized skill. The difficulty is that no one tells you they need doing until the consequence arrives, at which point the cost of the repair is several multiples of the cost of the prevention. In a properly maintained household, one finds a seasonal checklist and a person who follows it. One's Agent can produce the checklist. The person, regrettably, must be supplied independently._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I need a seasonal home maintenance checklist.
My home: [house / apartment / condo / rental — if renting,
note what maintenance is your responsibility vs. landlord's]
My region: [city or climate zone — this affects timing for
winterizing, pest prevention, hurricane/wildfire prep, etc.]
My home's specifics: [age of home, type of heating/cooling,
roof type, basement or crawl space, septic or municipal
sewer, any known issues]
Current season approaching: [spring / summer / fall / winter]
My skill level: [total beginner / can handle basic tools /
fairly handy]
Please:
1. Give me the complete checklist for the approaching season,
   in priority order --- most consequential if skipped first
2. For each task, tell me: what it prevents, how long it takes,
   whether I can do it myself, and estimated cost if I hire out
3. Flag anything that's time-sensitive --- tasks with a deadline
   (before first freeze, before rainy season, etc.)
4. Separate "essential" tasks from "ideal" tasks --- I may not
   get to everything
5. Note which tasks a renter should request from their landlord
   and how to make that request
:::
*What to do with the Output:* Put the deadlines on your calendar now --- not the tasks, just the deadlines. "Check gutters before November 15" is more useful than a checklist you save and forget. Set a recurring reminder for each season. After one full year, you will have a personalized maintenance calendar that accounts for your specific home, and the emergency repair calls will drop dramatically. If nobody in your family owned a home before you, none of this was obvious --- you learned by emergency, and each emergency cost more than the maintenance would have. This checklist is the institutional knowledge you were not given.

::: science
Preventive maintenance reduces home repair costs by an estimated 1--4% of the home's value per year --- for a $300,000 home, that is $3,000--$12,000 annually in avoided emergency repairs.[^ch10-1] HVAC systems that receive regular filter changes and annual servicing last 15--20 years; neglected systems fail at 8--12 years. Gutter cleaning prevents water damage that averages $2,500--$7,000 to repair. The economics are unambiguous: the cheapest repair is the one you prevent.
:::


::: tip
Ask your Agent to build the checklist as a calendar you can import. Most Agents can output tasks in a format you can paste into Google Calendar, Apple Reminders, or a shared household calendar. The checklist on the fridge works too --- but the one that sends you a notification on October 15 saying "clean gutters this weekend" works better.
:::


::: fairness
Renters: most of this checklist is your landlord's responsibility, and they may not be doing it. Your Agent can help you identify which seasonal maintenance items are legally the landlord's obligation in your state, draft a written request, and document the request in case the landlord does not act. See Ho-4: Knowing Your Rights as a Renter for the full framework. Preventing damage to the unit protects you --- deferred maintenance that causes damage can turn into a security deposit dispute, and the tenant who documented their maintenance requests in writing wins that dispute.
:::


[^ch10-1]: Preventive maintenance cost estimates derive from industry consensus (National Association of Home Builders, Freddie Mac homeowner guides, Fannie Mae). The 1--4% of home value per year range accounts for home age: newer homes trend toward 1%, older homes toward 3--4%.

---

#### Ch-11: Managing Subscriptions and Recurring Costs
*Strategy:* Decode + Assert
*See also:* M-1: Understanding Your Bank Account (for spotting charges), M-2: Understanding Your Credit Card Statement (for the audit trail), IRL-2: Customer Service Calls (for the cancellation call)
*My Man Jeeves:* _One might observe that the subscription model has achieved a remarkable efficiency: it converts a single purchasing decision into an indefinite revenue stream, secured by the knowledge that the consumer will, in the majority of cases, forget it exists. The average American maintains approximately 12 paid subscriptions and underestimates the monthly total by roughly 80% --- a gap between perception and expenditure that the industry has, one cannot help but notice, very little incentive to close. Cancellation, when attempted, encounters a friction that is precisely calibrated: not so difficult as to invite regulatory scrutiny, but sufficiently inconvenient to discourage all but the most determined. In well-managed households, a financial officer reviews recurring charges quarterly. One's Agent is capable of conducting this audit in approximately ten minutes, provided one is willing to look at the number._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I need to audit my subscriptions and recurring charges.
Here is my information: [choose one or more]
— I'll paste my credit card or bank statement showing
  recurring charges: [paste the charges]
— Subscriptions I know about: [list them with monthly cost]
— I think I'm paying for things I don't use but I'm not
  sure what
Please:
1. Identify every recurring charge and categorize them:
   actively using / occasionally using / forgot I had this /
   free trial I never cancelled
2. Calculate my total monthly and annual subscription spend
3. Flag any charges that look like they've increased since
   I signed up (common with introductory pricing)
4. For each subscription I want to cancel, tell me exactly
   how to cancel --- website path, phone number, what to say,
   and any retention offers I might be offered
5. Identify where I'm paying for overlapping services
   (multiple streaming, multiple cloud storage, etc.)
:::
*What to do with the Output:* Cancel at least one thing today. Not tomorrow, not "this weekend" --- today. The activation energy for subscription cancellation drops to zero if you do the first one immediately. For services with cancellation dark patterns (looking at you, every gym and cable company), see IRL-2: Customer Service Calls for the exact script.

::: science
A 2022 C+R Research survey found that the average American spends $219 per month on subscriptions but estimates their spending at $86 --- a 154% underestimation gap.[^ch11-1] The behavioral economics are well-documented: subscription pricing exploits status quo bias (the tendency to leave existing arrangements in place) and the "pain of paying" asymmetry (signing up feels like one small charge; cancelling feels like giving something up). Companies know this. The cancellation flow is designed around it. Your Agent does not have status quo bias. It sees a number.
:::


::: meme
The "free trial to paid subscription" pipeline is the Hotel California of consumer finance: you can check out any time you like, but you can never leave. Or rather, you can leave, but only by navigating a cancellation flow that requires you to call during business hours, talk to a "retention specialist," decline three increasingly desperate offers, and confirm twice that yes, you really do want to cancel the thing you never used. Your Agent can map the cancellation path before you start, so you know exactly what to expect and what to say.
:::


::: tip
Set a quarterly calendar reminder: "subscription audit." Paste your most recent credit card statement into your Agent and ask it to flag every recurring charge. This takes ten minutes and saves, on average, $50--$100 per quarter in forgotten or unused subscriptions. The reminder is the system. Without it, you will not do this.
:::


::: fairness
"Dark patterns" --- user interface designs that trick or pressure consumers into actions they did not intend --- are not accidents. They are designed, tested, and optimized. The FTC finalized a "click to cancel" rule in 2024 requiring that cancelling be as easy as signing up, though the rule was vacated on appeal in 2025 and its enforcement remains in litigation.[^ch11-2] If a company makes you call to cancel a service you signed up for online, that is a dark pattern. Your Agent can identify these, draft a complaint to the FTC if you want to file one, and help you navigate the cancellation process that was designed to make you give up.
:::


[^ch11-1]: C+R Research. (2022). ["Consumer Subscription Spending Report."](https://www.crresearch.com/blog/too-many-satisfactions-consumers-overestimate-subscription-spending/) Survey of 1,000 US consumers found average monthly subscription spend of $219 vs. self-estimated $86.
[^ch11-2]: Federal Trade Commission. (2024). ["Click-to-Cancel Rule."](https://www.ftc.gov/legal-library/browse/federal-register-notices/negative-option-rule) Finalized October 2024; vacated by the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals, July 2025. Status in flux at time of publication.
